%U A375120 1,3,1,15,1,1,2,2,1,3,1,9,2,1,1,9,1,1,1
%N A375120 Number of complete binary unordered tree-factorizations of n.
%C A375120 For prime n, the factorization tree is a single vertex in just one way so that a(n) = 1.
%C A375120 For composite n, the two subtrees at n are a split of n into an unordered pair of factors {d, n/d}; a split with d = n/d contributes binomial(a(d)+1, 2) trees (unordered pairs with repetition), so a(n) = Sum_{d|n, 2 <= d < sqrt(n)} a(d)*a(n/d) + [n is a perfect square]*binomial(a(sqrt(n))+1, 2). - corrected by _Giuseppe Barbalinardo_, Jul 08 2026
%C A375120 a(1) = 1 is by convention, reckoning 1 as having a single empty factorization.
%C A375120 On prime powers, a(p^k) = A001190(k), the Wedderburn-Etherington number of unordered binary trees with k leaves; a(n) depends only on the multiset of exponents in the prime factorization of n. - _Giuseppe Barbalinardo_, Jul 08 2026
%H A375120 Giuseppe Barbalinardo, <a href="/A375120/b375120.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A375120 Giuseppe Barbalinardo, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.21252898">Prime-Leaf Tree Theory: arithmetic as the statistical mechanics of multiplication histories</a>, preprint, 2026.
%F A375120 From _Giuseppe Barbalinardo_, Jul 08 2026: (Start)
%F A375120 a(1) = 1; a(p) = 1 for prime p; for composite n, a(n) = (1/2)*(Sum_{d|n, 1 < d < n} a(d)*a(n/d) + [n is a perfect square]*a(sqrt(n))).
%F A375120 Let Z(s) = Sum_{n>=2} a(n)/n^s. Then Z(s) = P(s) + (Z(s)^2 + Z(2s))/2, where P is the prime zeta function; the abscissa of convergence is 1.98847685... . (End)
%e A375120 For n = 4, the a(4) = 1 sole factor tree is
%e A375120      4     4 = 2*2
%e A375120     / \
%e A375120    2   2
%e A375120 For n=12, the a(12) = 2 factor trees are
%e A375120     12          12
%e A375120    /  \        /  \
%e A375120   2    6      3    4
%e A375120       / \         / \
%e A375120      2   3       2   2
%e A375120 The tree structures are the same but the values are not the same and are therefore distinct factorizations.
%o A375120 (SageMath)
%o A375120 @cached_function
%o A375120 def a(n):
%o A375120     if is_prime(n) or n == 1: return 1
%o A375120     T = [t for t in divisors(n) if 1 < t <= n/t]
%o A375120     return sum(binomial(a(d)+1, 2) if d*d == n else a(d)*a(n//d) for d in T)
%o A375120 print([a(n) for n in range(1, 88)])  # _Peter Luschny_, Nov 03 2024, corrected by _Giuseppe Barbalinardo_, Jul 08 2026
%Y A375120 Cf. A281119, A292505, A007964 (a(n)=1), A058080 (a(n)>1), A001190 (values on prime powers), A144757 (ordered version), A008480.
